Creating Choropleth maps with ggplot2

Learning objectives

In this lesson, you will mainly learn how to use ggplot() and geom_sf() to create nice choropleth maps.

More specifically, you will learn how to:

  1. Matching raw data to polygons

    • Get boundaries/polygons
    • Get disease related data
    • Join by admnistrative level

  2. Applying Color scaling for continuous and discrete variables

    • Continuous
    • Discre

  3. Applying Facet Wrap and Grid

    • Creating small multiples and using facet_wrap()
    • Creating small multiples and using facet_grid()

1 Introduction

A choropleth map is a thematic map in which geographic regions are shaded or patterned in proportion to the value of a variable being represented. This variable can be an epidemiological indicator such as disease prevalence or mortality rate. Choropleth maps are particularly useful for visualizing spatial patterns and variations across different regions.

The essential components of a choropleth map include:

Geographic Regions: These are the areas that will be represented on the map, such as countries, states, districts, or any other geographic divisions.

Data Values: These are the values associated with each geographic region that will be represented on the map, including population density, prevalence, incidence, mortality rate, etc.

Color Scale: This is the range of colors used to represent the different data values. Typically, a gradient of colors is used, with lighter colors representing lower values and darker colors representing higher values.

[FINAL IMAGE HERE]

Choropleth maps have several notable advantages:

  • Visual Clarity: They provide a clear visual representation of the spatial distribution of data, making it easier to identify patterns and trends.

  • Ease of Understanding: They are intuitive and easy to understand, even for individuals without specialized knowledge in the field.

  • Versatility: They can be used to represent a wide variety of data, making them suitable for various applications.

However, there are also important limitations to be aware of:

  • Data Sensitivity: The appearance of the map can be significantly affected by the choice of data classification and color scale.

  • Geographic Size Bias: Larger regions may appear more prominent on the map, leading to visual bias.

In the following section, you will learn how to create a choropleth map using the ggplot2 package in R.

2 Data Preparation

Before creating a choropleth map, it is essential to prepare the data. The data should contain the geographic regions and the values you want to visualize.

In this section, you will go through the data preparation process, which includes the following steps:

  1. Import polygon data: This is the geographical data that contains the boundaries of each region that you want to include in your map.

  2. Import attribute data: This is the data that contains the values you want to visualize on the map, such as disease prevalence, population density, etc.

  3. Join the polygon and attribute data: This step involves merging the polygon data with the attribute data based on a common identifier, such as the administrative level or region name. This will create a single dataset that contains both the geographic boundaries and the corresponding data values.

Now, lets go through each step in detail.

2.1 Step 1: Import polygon data

Polygons are closed shapes with three or more sides. In spatial data, polygons are used to represent areas such as the boundary of a city, lake, or any land use type. They are essential in geographical information systems (GIS) for tasks like mapping, spatial analysis, and land cover classification.

Shapefiles are a common format for storing spatial data. They consist of at least three files with extensions .shp (shape), .shx (index), and .dbf (attribute data).

[REFER TO SPATIAL VIZ COURSE]

You can read shapefiles in R using the sf package.

# Reading the shapefile
eth_adm1 <- sf::st_read(here::here("data/raw/ETH_Adm1_shapefile/ETH_Adm_1.shp"))

The important elements of any ggplot layer are the aesthetic mappings aes(x,y, ) which tell ggplot where to place the plot objects. We can imagine a map just like a graph with all features mapping to an x and y axis. All geometry (geom_) types in ggplot feature some kind of aesthetic mapping, and these can either be declared at the plot level, e.g.,

Below you can see that geom_sf() is used to trace the boundaries of the different regions of Ethiopia. Similarly, different layers can be added on top.

ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data = eth_adm1)+
  labs(title = "Ethiopia Shapefile Overview")

Here, we first read the Ethiopia shapefile using sf::st_read() and then plot it using ggplot2. The geom_sf() function is used to render the spatial data, and labs() is used to add a title to the plot.

2.2 Step 2: Import Attribute Data

# Reading the attribute data
tb_cases <- read_csv(here::here("data/tb_cases.csv"))

2.3 Step 3: Join Data by Administrative Levels

Now well get the data we want to plot on the map. Here, well just make the data up, but you can import a CSV of it or extract it from your model estimates. The important thing is that the ID numbers are the same in the shapefile as in your data you want to plot, because that will be necessary for them to merge properly (you could also merge by the name itself).

Before joining the two datasets, we need to define the join key (by =).

# Add population data and calculate cases per 10K population
tb <- eth_adm1 %>% 
     left_join(tb_cases,                        
               by = c("NAME_1")) %>% 
     st_as_sf() # convert to shapefile

You can keep only the important variables that will be used in the construction of the plots.

Reminder: You can check the names of all your columns by using names().

In this step, we first read the TB cases data using read_csv(). Then, we merge the shapefile data eth_adm1 with the TB cases data tb_cases using left_join() from the dplyr package. The by argument is used to specify the common column(s) on which to merge the datasets. Finally, we convert the merged data to a shapefile using st_as_sf().

2.4 Checking and Validating the Joined Data

It is essential to check and validate the joined data to ensure that the merge was successful and the data is accurate.

# Validate the joined data
all.equal(unique(eth_adm1$NAME_1), unique(tb_cases$NAME_1))
## [1] TRUE

In this code chunk, we compare the unique region names in the eth_adm1 and tb_cases datasets using all.equal() to ensure that all the regions in the shapefile are matched with the corresponding regions in the attribute data. If the merge was successful, all.equal() should return TRUE. Otherwise, it will return a detailed description of the differences between the two sets of region names.

In this part of the lesson, you learned about the importance of administrative levels in spatial data and how to join spatial and attribute data by administrative levels using the dplyr package in R and how to check and validate the joined data.

3 Creating a Beautiful Choropleth Map with ggplot2

3.1 Using the Fill Variable (i.e., Attribute Variable)

To display the number of cases, you need to fill the polygons drawn with geom_sf() using the fill variable. This is very straightforward as it follows the same logic as the syntax of ggplot2 package.

ggplot(data=tb) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill=cases)) +   # set fill to vary by case count variable
  labs(title = "Ethiopia TB Distributed Cases")

3.2 Customizing the Map

ggplot(data=tb) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill=cases)) +   # set fill to vary by case count variable
  labs(title = "Ethiopia TB Distributed Cases",
       fill = "Number of Cases") +
  xlab("Longitude")+
  ylab("Latitude")+
  ggspatial::annotation_north_arrow(location = "br")+
  ggspatial::annotation_scale(location = "bl")+
  theme_bw()

In the first code chunk, we create a basic choropleth map using ggplot2. The fill aesthetic is set to vary by the cases variable, which colors the regions based on the number of TB cases.

In the second code chunk, we customize the map by adding titles to the axes and the legend, adding a north arrow and scale bar using ggspatial::annotation_north_arrow() and ggspatial::annotation_scale(), and changing the theme to theme_bw().

4 Color Scaling

4.1 Color Scaling for Continuous Attributes

The scale_fill_continuous() function from the ggplot2 package in R is used to apply continuous color scaling to a choropleth map.

You can customize the color palette used for continuous color scaling by specifying the low and high parameters in the scale_fill_continuous() function.

# Create a ggplot object
ggplot(data = tb) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = cases))+
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "green", high = "red")+ # apply continuous color scaling
  theme_bw()

In this section, you learned about continuous data and its importance in choropleth maps. You also learned how to apply continuous color scaling to a choropleth map using the scale_fill_continuous() function from the ggplot2 package in R and how to customize the color palette.

4.2 Color Scaling for Discrete Attributes

Discrete data is a type of quantitative data that can only take specific, separate values. It is often the result of counting objects or events. Discrete data is important in choropleth maps as it allows us to represent the count or quantity of objects or events in different regions. Using distinct colors or patterns to represent discrete data helps in visualizing the data distribution and identifying patterns, trends, and outliers.

The scale_fill_brewer() function from the ggplot2 package in R is used to apply discrete color scaling to a choropleth map.

Before applying the discrete color scaling, you will need to create a new discrete column, which could be a risk level based on the number of cases. For this, you can use mutate() combined with case_when().

tb %>%
  mutate(risk = case_when(cases < quantile(cases, 0.5) ~ 'low',
                          cases > quantile(cases, 0.75) ~ 'high', 
                          TRUE ~ 'medium')) -> tb2

ggplot(data = tb2) + # Create a ggplot object
  geom_sf(aes(fill =  fct_reorder(risk, cases)))+ # reorder the risk labels according to the number of cases
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set4", "Risk levels")+ # set palette and rename legend
  theme_bw()

You can also create a custom color palette for discrete variables.

custom_palette <- c("green", "yellow", "red") # create a custom color palette manually

# Apply custom color palette
ggplot(data = tb2) + # Create a ggplot object
   geom_sf(aes(fill =  fct_reorder(risk, cases)))+ # reorder the risk labels according to the number of cases
   scale_fill_manual(values = custom_palette, "Risk levels") + 
   coord_sf(expand = TRUE)+
   theme_bw()

In this lesson, you learned about discrete data and its importance in choropleth maps. You also learned how to apply discrete color scaling to a choropleth map using the scale_fill_brewer() function from the ggplot2 package in R and how to customize the color palette.

5 Facet Wrap vs.Grid

  • facet_wrap(): This function wraps a 1D sequence of panels into 2D. This is useful when you have a single variable with many levels and want to arrange the plots in a more space-efficient manner.
  • facet_grid(): This function creates a matrix of panels defined by row and column faceting variables. It is most useful when you have two discrete variables, and all combinations of the variables exist in the data.
  • facet_wrap() is used for single variable faceting, while facet_grid() is used for two-variable faceting.
  • facet_wrap() arranges the panels in a 2D grid, while facet_grid() arranges them in a matrix.

5.1 Creating Small Multiples using facet_wrap()

You can use the facet_wrap() function to create small multiples based on a given variable. In the following example, you can use the year variable.

Note: Remember that color scaling can be adjusted by scale_fill_continuous() if the variable is continuous or by scale_fill_brewer() if the variable is discrete.

# Create ggplot object using facet_wrap
ggplot(data = tb) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = cases)) +
  facet_wrap(~ year)+
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "green", high = "red") + # apply continuous color scaling
  theme_bw()

Creating Small Multiples using facet_grid()

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = eth_adm1) + # need the 
  geom_sf(aes(fill = cases), data = tb2) +
  facet_wrap(year ~ risk)+
  coord_sf(expand = TRUE)+
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "green", high = "red")+
  theme_bw()

There remains only one concern, which is the overlapping of the x-axis!

Here, geom_sf() should work seamlessly with ggplot2::scale_*_continuous(), where you can use the breaks = argument.

In the last plot, you will notice that we used a continuous fill variable, but we also used a facet_wrap on two other discrete variables.

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = eth_adm1) + # need the 
  geom_sf(aes(fill = cases), data = tb2) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(34, 48, by = 4)) +
  facet_wrap(year ~ risk)+
  coord_sf(expand = TRUE)+
  scale_fill_continuous(low = "green", high = "red")+
  labs(title = "Distribution of cases and risk levels of TB in Ethiopia",
       subtitle = "2020-2021")+
  xlab("Longitude")+
  ylab("Latitude")+
  theme_bw()

In this section, you learned the differences between facet_wrap() and facet_grid(), and how to create small multiples using both of these functions.
